re volcanic spark discharge generates all three Strecker reagents (HCN, CH2O, NH3) simultaneously\u2014directly supported by Miller's original work and Johnson et al. (2008) re-analysis. The volcanic apparatus preferentially produces hydroxylated amino acids. The formose step converts CH2O to glycolaldehyde needed for serine vs. glycine. Environmental progression is all Surface\u2192Biochemical (no hydrothermal stage), which is valid but less diverse.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Note that Johnson et al. 2008 volcanic apparatus specifically enhanced serine production via OH radical hydroxylation\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.83,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.92,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n            \"feedback\": \"Elegant and concise pathway directly implementing Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic protometabolism. Glycolaldehyde as an 'inevitable by-product' of HCN/H2S photoredox chemistry feeds directly into Strecker synthesis. This is one of the strongest literature-supported routes. The reaction rxn_005 is slightly simplified\u2014the full Patel mechanism involves Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and phosphate buffer\u2014but the essential chemistry is correct. NH3 source needed externally.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox and UV irradiation conditions for rxn_005 to better reflect Patel et al. mechanism\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_s